                        <a class="story-card__series" href="https://www.propublica.org/series/criminal-justice-rollback">Criminal Justice Rollback</a>
        
        <h3 class="story-card__hed" >
            <a href="https://www.propublica.org/article/lloyd-gray-louisiana-split-juries-history">
                                    What One Man’s 45-Year-Old Case Tells Us About the “Jim Crow Juries” Haunting Louisiana
                            </a>
        </h3>

        <p class="story-card__dek" >
                            Today, a split verdict would mean a mistrial. But in 1980s Louisiana, when nonunanimous juries were still legal, 19-year-old Lloyd Gray, a Black man, was sentenced to prison for life — even though the only two Black jurors had voted not guilty.
                    </p>

        <p class="story-card__byline">
                        <span class="story-card__byline-author">
                by <span class="name">Richard A. Webster</span>, <a href="https://veritenews.org/">Verite News</a>,
            </span>
                        <span class="story-card__byline-dateline">
                <time class="timestamp" datetime="2025-09-02EDT05:00">Sept. 2, 2025, 5 a.m. EDT</time>
            </span>
        </p>

                <p class="story-card__unit">Local Reporting Network</p>
            </div>
